'''Patricia Anne Boyd''' (born 17 March 1944) is an English model and photographer. She was one of the leading international models during the 1960s and, with [[Jean Shrimpton]], epitomised the British female "look" of the era. Boyd was married to [[George Harrison]] and experienced the height of [[the Beatles]]' popularity as well as sharing in their embrace of Indian spirituality. She later married and divorced Harrison's friend, guitarist [[Eric Clapton]]. Boyd inspired Harrison's songs such as "[[If I Needed Someone]]", "[[Something (Beatles song)|Something]]" and "[[For You Blue]]", and Clapton's "[[Layla]]" and "[[Wonderful Tonight]]".

In August 2007, Boyd published her autobiography ''[[Wonderful Today]]''<ref name="RS/SpillsBeans" /> (titled ''Wonderful Tonight'' in the United States). Her photographs of Harrison and Clapton, titled ''Through the Eye of a Muse'', have been exhibited in [[Dublin]], [[Sydney]], [[Toronto]], [[Moscow]], [[London]], [[Almaty]], [[Uppsala]] and throughout the United States.

==Early life==
Boyd was born on 17 March 1944,{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=4}} in [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]],<ref name=bbcsomerset>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/somerset/content/articles/2007/08/28/patti_boyd_feature.shtml|publisher=BBC Somerset|title=Profiles: Pattie Boyd's extraordinary life|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> and was the first child to Colin Ian Langdon Boyd{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=7}} and Diana Frances Boyd (née Drysdale). The Boyds moved to [[West Lothian]] in Scotland, where her brother, Colin, was born in 1946.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=3}} They then moved to [[Guildford]], Surrey, where her sister, [[Jenny Boyd]], was born in 1947.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=6}} Boyd's youngest sister, Paula, was born at a hospital in [[Nakuru]], Kenya, in 1951.{{sfn|Boyd|2007}} The Boyds lived in [[Nairobi]] from 1948 to 1953, after her father's discharge from the [[Royal Air Force]].{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=7}} The family returned to England, where Boyd gained two half-brothers, David (b. 1954) and Robert Jr. (b. 1955),<ref name="BoydBookAmazon"/> as well as two half-sisters, Clare (1962–2018) and Julia (b. 1964).

Boyd attended Hazeldean School in [[Putney]], the St Agnes and St Michael Convent Boarding School in [[East Grinstead]], and St Martha's Convent in [[Hadley Wood]], Hertfordshire. She achieved three [[General Certificate of Education|GCE]] [[GCE Ordinary Level|O level]] passes in 1961.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=36}} She moved to London in 1962 and worked as a shampoo girl at [[Elizabeth Arden]]'s salon. A client who worked for ''[[Honey (magazine)|Honey]]'' magazine then inspired her to begin work as a model.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=35, 40–41}}

==Career==
===Modelling===
Boyd began her fashion career in 1962,{{sfn|Harry|2003|pp=32–33}} modelling at first in London and [[Paris]].{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=50}} Among her regular assignments at that time were jobs for the [[Vogue (British magazine)|UK edition]] of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' in France, and ''Honey'', as well as fashion spreads in newspapers such as ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' and ''[[The Times]]''.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=50}} She was photographed by [[David Bailey (photographer)|David Bailey]], [[Terence Donovan (photographer)|Terence Donovan]] and [[Brian Duffy (photographer)|Brian Duffy]], among others,{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=49}} and appeared on the cover of British ''Vogue''.<ref name="RockMuseRemembers">{{cite web|first=Anthony|last=Mason|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/08/23/sunday/main3198902.shtml|title=A Rock Muse Remembers|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=26 August 2007|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> Other popular models of the day, such as [[Twiggy]], based their modelling appearance on Boyd.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|pp=499, 909}}{{refn|group=nb|[[Kim Kerrigan]], who had a natural resemblance to Boyd, changed her first name from Patsy in 1964, to avoid the perception that she and the agency representing her might be attempting to "cash in" on Boyd's popularity.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|pp=112–13}}}} In the description of journalist [[Tom Hibbert]], Boyd and [[Jean Shrimpton]] became "international celebrities" as the embodiment of the "British female 'look' – mini-skirt, long, straight hair and wide-eyed loveliness". This look defined Western fashion for women as a result of the international popularity of [[the Beatles]] and other [[British Invasion]] musical acts from 1964 onwards.<ref name="Hibbert/HistoryOfRock">{{cite magazine|first=Tom|last=Hibbert|title=Britain invades the world: Mid-Sixties British Music|magazine=[[The History of Rock (magazine)|The History of Rock]]|year=1982}} Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/britain-invades-the-world-mid-sixties-british-music Rock's Backpages] (subscription required).</ref> In her autobiography, Boyd recalls being known as the muse to designer [[Ossie Clark]], who used to call some of his designs "Pattie".{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=53}}{{refn|group=nb|Boyd's first name was often abbreviated to "Patti" also.{{sfn|Harry|2003|pp=32–33}}}}

In early 1964, Boyd appeared in a television advertising campaign for [[The Smith's Snackfood Company|Smith's crisps]], directed by [[Richard Lester]].{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=33}} Lester then cast her as a schoolgirl in the Beatles' 1964 film ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'',{{sfn|Barrow|2006|p=243}}<ref name="NewYorkTimesreview">{{cite news|first=Bosley|last=Crowther|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/21522/A-Hard-Day-s-Night/overview|title=A Hard Day's Night (1964)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=19 February 2007|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> where she met and befriended the group's lead guitarist, [[George Harrison]].{{sfn|Tillery|2011|p=29}}{{refn|group=nb|Her only line in the film was "Prisoners?",{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=33}} but she later appeared in the "[[I Should Have Known Better]]" segment.{{sfn|Huntley|2006|p=86}}}} Boyd's modelling career skyrocketed as a result of her subsequent romantic involvement with Harrison.<ref name="Hibbert/HistoryOfRock" />{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=201}} She recalls that further assignments for ''Vogue'' and ''Vanity Fair'' were the result, along with jobs for ''[[Tatler]]'' (with photographer [[Jeanloup Sieff]]), more TV commercials, for Smith's and for [[L'Oréal]]'s Dop shampoo brand, and advertisements in newspaper fashion pages.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=70–71}} 

Boyd and Harrison were among the leading couples in the [[Swinging London]] era, when, according to a 1966 article in the ''[[Daily Express]]'', "actors, pop singers, hairdressers, and models" were London's new "privileged class".{{sfn|Turner|2016|pp=330–31}} [[UK underground]] writer [[Barry Miles]] later described her as "by far the most glamorous" of all the Beatles' wives and girlfriends,{{sfn|Miles|2001|p=136}} while author [[Shawn Levy (writer)|Shawn Levy]] writes that, even more so than [[Jane Asher]], the London-born stage actress who was [[Paul McCartney]]'s girlfriend for much of the 1960s, Boyd epitomised what "sixties stardom was meant to confer upon its chosen".{{sfn|Levy|2003|p=177}}{{refn|group=nb|Levy adds: "''That'' was why a provincial boy learned how to play bar chords and sing harmony and hitchhiked down the [[Great North Road (Great Britain)|Great Northern Road]] to the capital!"{{sfn|Levy|2003|p=177}}}} Writing in 1966, British fashion designer [[Mary Quant]] commented that it had become a requisite for contemporary women to strive "to look like Pattie Boyd rather than [[Marlene Dietrich]]", adding: "Their aim is to look childishly young, naïvely unsophisticated, and it takes more sophistication to work out that look than those early would-be sophisticates ever dreamed of."{{sfn|Clayson|2003|pp=167, 476}}

At the request of [[Gloria Stavers]],{{sfn|Barrow|2006|p=243}} Boyd began writing a column, titled "Patti's Letter from London", for the American teen magazine ''[[16 Magazine|16]]''.{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=34}} According to Hibbert: "She reported on the latest trends in [[Carnaby Street]], informed readers as to what the Beatles and [[The Rolling Stones|Stones]] were wearing at the moment, and gave advice on how to turn dark and curly hair straight and blonde."<ref name="Hibbert/HistoryOfRock" /> However, with Boyd the target of hostility from the Beatles' female fans, Harrison insisted she abandon her career, to ensure their privacy.{{sfn|Harry|2003|pp=34, 35}} In July 1968, she and her sister Jenny, who was also a model, opened a boutique in London's fashionable [[Chelsea Market]]. They named it "Jennifer Juniper" after [[Donovan]]'s [[Jennifer Juniper|song of the same name]].{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=63}} Jenny managed the shop, which sold antiques and other ''objets d'art'', while Boyd was the buyer.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=137–38}}

Boyd says she had "virtually given up" modelling by the early 1970s.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=135}} She resumed her career at that time,{{sfn|Huntley|2006|p=87}} promoting designs by Ossie Clark.{{sfn|Greene|2006|p=198}} She and Twiggy then did a cover assignment in [[Milan]] for [[Vogue Italia|Italian ''Vogue'']] with photographer [[Justin de Villeneuve]], and, working again with Bailey, Boyd appeared on several covers for British ''Vogue''. In another shoot for the latter magazine, Boyd and her sisters were photographed by [[Patrick Lichfield]].{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=135–36}}

===Photography===
Boyd began taking photographs of musicians and other friends during the 1960s and was a member of the [[Royal Photographic Society]].{{cn|date=August 2018}} In a 2008 interview, she said that it was not until 2004 that she felt "emotionally ready" to revisit the images. She also said that her lack of professional status probably made for a more intimate and authentic mood in her work, since her subjects were relaxed in her company.<ref name="Balfe/Ent.ie">{{cite web|first=John|last=Balfe|title=Interview with Pattie Boyd |url=http://entertainment.ie/music/feature/Interview-with-Pattie-Boyd/201/42.htm|publisher=[[entertainment.ie]]|date=28 August 2018|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Boyd first exhibited her photos of Harrison and Clapton at the [[San Francisco Art Exchange]] on [[Valentine's Day]] 2005, in a show titled ''Through the Eye of a Muse''.<ref name="CNN2005"/> The exhibition appeared in San Francisco and London during 2006, and in [[La Jolla, California]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pattie Boyd Opening at La Jolla Gallery April 2008|url=https://www.morrisonhotelgallery.com/set/default.aspx?setID=555|publisher=Morrison Hotel Gallery|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> ''Through the Eye of a Muse'' was also shown in Dublin<ref name="Balfe/Ent.ie" /> and in Toronto in 2008, and at the Blender Gallery in Sydney<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/arts/fab-faces-of-swinging-60s/2009/12/01/1259429373581.html|title=Fab faces of swinging '60s|first=Adam|last=Fulton|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=2 December 2009|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> and in Almaty, Kazakhstan, in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/arts_n_ideas/article/beatles-clapton-pics-in-free-show/440756.html|title=Beatles, Clapton Pics in Free Show|first=Olga|last=Kuzmina|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=19 July 2011|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bajanreporter.com/2009/12/the-old-pharmacy-gallery-in-speightstown-soon-to-host-movie-classics-lanster-2010-season/|title=The Old Pharmacy Gallery in Speightstown – Soon To Host Movie Classics & Lancaster 2010 Season|work=Bajan Reporter|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>

Her exhibition ''Yesterday and Today: The Beatles and Eric Clapton'' was shown in [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Santa Catalina Island]] in California,<ref>{{cite news|date=3 July 2011|first=Louis|last=Sahagun|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|title=An ex-Beatle wife brings the Age of Aquarius back to Catalina Island|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jul/03/local/la-me-pattie-20110703}}</ref> and at the National Geographic Headquarters in Washington, DC, in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|date=29 September 2011|author=unknown|title=Music on&nbsp;... Photography: Pattie Boyd|url=http://events.nationalgeographic.com/events/speakers/2011/10/12/music-photography-pattie-boyd/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924041410/http://events.nationalgeographic.com/events/speakers/2011/10/12/music-photography-pattie-boyd/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=24 September 2011}}</ref>

===Charity work===
Boyd became involved in charity work following her separation from Clapton in the late 1980s. In 1991, she co-founded SHARP (Self Help Addiction Recovery Program) with [[Barbara Bach]], the second wife of former Beatle [[Ringo Starr]].{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=40}}

==Personal life==

===Marriage to George Harrison===
[[File:Kinfauns George Harrison house.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Kinfauns, the home of Pattie Boyd and George Harrison from 1965 to 1970]]

Boyd was in a relationship with photographer Eric Swayne{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=56, 60}} when she met Harrison, on 2 March 1964,{{sfn|Miles|2001|pp=135–36}} and therefore declined his initial date proposal.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=499}} Several days later, having ended the relationship with Swayne, she accompanied Harrison to a private [[gentlemen's club]] called the [[Garrick Club]], chaperoned by the Beatles' manager, [[Brian Epstein]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Varjgas|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/SummerConcert/story?id=3546199&page=1|title=The Real 'Layla' Talks About George Harrison and Eric Clapton|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=31 August 2007|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> With the Beatles frequently away on concert tours, she and Harrison subsequently saw each other as often as their professional commitments allowed.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=68, 70}} In July 1964,{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=242}} Harrison bought [[Kinfauns (George Harrison)|Kinfauns]], a house in [[Esher]], Surrey, to escape the constant attention of fans in central London,{{sfn|Barrow|2006|p=243}} and Boyd soon moved into the house also.{{sfn|Levy|2003|p=228}}

Boyd had her first encounter with [[LSD]] in early 1965{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=565}} when the couple's dentist, John Riley,{{sfn|Tillery|2011|p=44}} secretly laced his guests' coffee with the drug during a dinner party at his home.<ref name="CNN2005"/> As she was getting ready to leave with Harrison and [[John Lennon|John]] and [[Cynthia Lennon]], Riley told them that he had spiked their drinks and tried to persuade them to stay.{{sfn|Tillery|2011|p=45}} Outside, Boyd was in an agitated state from the drug and threatened to break a store window, but Harrison pulled her away.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|pp=565–566}} Later, when Boyd and her group were in a lift on their way up to the Ad Lib club, they mistakenly believed it was on fire.{{sfn|Tillery|2011|p=45}}

The couple were engaged on 25 December 1965, and married on 21 January 1966{{sfn|Turner|1999|p=219}} in a ceremony at [[Epsom]] [[register office]].{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=57}} In his "How a Beatle Lives" profile in the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' in March 1966, Harrison stressed the equality of their relationship and credited Boyd with broadening his outlook.{{sfn|Gould|2007|p=311}} In September and October, after the Beatles' [[The Beatles' 1966 US tour|final concert tour]], Boyd and Harrison spent six weeks in India,{{sfn|Gould|2007|p=367}} as guests of Indian classical musician [[Ravi Shankar]].{{sfn|Spitz|2005|pp=644–45}}{{sfn|Tillery|2011|pp=56–57}} While in [[Mumbai|Bombay]], as Harrison continued his [[sitar]] studies under Shankar's tutelage,{{sfn|Barrow|2006|p=216}} Boyd began learning to play the [[dilruba]], a bow-played string instrument.{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=201}} Due to the attention of fans and the press, they left the city with Shankar and stayed on houseboats on [[Dal Lake]] in [[Kashmir]].{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=88}}{{sfn|Greene|2006|p=127}} Upon their return to England, Boyd and Harrison continued to adhere to a lifestyle of [[yoga]] and [[vegetarianism]],{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=208}}{{sfn|Tillery|2011|p=58}} and Boyd received further tuition on the dilruba from [[Shiv Dayal Batish]].{{sfn|Kruth|2015|pp=75–76}}{{refn|group=nb|Batish described her as a "smart student" who quickly mastered the basics of the instrument.{{sfn|Kruth|2015|p=76}}}}

On 25 June 1967, Boyd was among the crowd of friends who participated in the Beatles' ''[[Our World (International TV special)|Our World]]'' broadcast of "[[All You Need Is Love]]".{{refn|group=nb|She was also one of the chorus singers on "[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]" in 1966 and sang the female vocal parts, with [[Yoko Ono]], on the 1968 song "[[Birthday (Beatles song)|Birthday]]".{{sfn|MacDonald|1998|pp=183, 277}}}} Boyd shared her husband's interest in Eastern [[mysticism]].{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=223}}{{sfn|Greene|2006|p=197}}<ref>{{cite book|first=Marianne|last=Faithfull|chapter=We Love You|year=2002|title=[[Mojo (magazine)#Special editions|Mojo Special Limited Edition]]: 1000 Days That Shook the World (The Psychedelic Beatles – April 1, 1965 to December 26, 1967)|location=London|publisher=Emap|p=146}}</ref> Having become a member of the [[Spiritual Regeneration Movement]] in February 1967, she was keen to meet the movement's leader, [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]], and so suggested that she and Harrison attend his lecture on [[Transcendental Meditation]] at the London Hilton on 24 August.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=95–96}}{{sfn|Clayson|2003|pp=223–24}} Impressed with the Maharishi, Harrison and Boyd, together with the other Beatles and their partners, travelled to a seminar he hosted [[The Beatles in Bangor|in Bangor, Wales]], the following day.<ref name="CNN2005">{{cite news|first=Todd|last=Lepold|url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/03/pattie.boyd/|title=Harrison, Clapton and their muse|publisher=CNN|date=3 February 2005|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Spitz|2005|pp=710–711}} Boyd and her sister Jenny then accompanied Harrison on [[The Beatles at Rishikesh|the Beatles' visit]] to the Maharishi's [[ashram]] in [[Rishikesh]], India, in February 1968.{{sfn|Turner|1999|p=219}} That same year, she told Beatles biographer [[Hunter Davies]] that the four Beatles had a bond that neither she nor any other wife could penetrate;{{sfn|Gould|2007|p=498}} she also said she wished that the band would use their fame and influence to publicly further a cause, as [[Marlon Brando]] had done on behalf of homeless children.{{sfn|Davies|2009|pp=324–25}} Boyd provided inspiration for several of Harrison's Beatles compositions, including "[[I Need You (Beatles song)|I Need You]]",{{sfn|Turner|1999|pp=78, 82}} "[[If I Needed Someone]]",{{sfn|Kruth|2015|p=103}} "[[Love You To]]", "[[Something (Beatles song)|Something]]"{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=271}}<ref>{{cite book|first=Ashley|last=Khan|chapter=Gun for Hire|year=2003|title=[[Mojo (magazine)#Special editions|Mojo Special Limited Edition]]: 1000 Days of Revolution (The Beatles' Final Years – Jan 1, 1968 to Sept 27, 1970)|location=London|publisher=Emap|p=48}}</ref> and "[[For You Blue]]".{{sfn|MacDonald|1998|pp=129, 172, 295}}{{refn|group=nb|Harrison later cited alternative sources of inspiration for "Something". In early 1969, by which point he had befriended members of the [[Hare Krishna movement]], he said that the song was about the Hindu deity [[Krishna]].{{sfn|Greene|2006|pp=141–42}}}} In March 1969, as part of the British authorities' intolerant attitude towards the Beatles in the late 1960s, Boyd and Harrison were arrested at Kinfauns for possession of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]].{{sfn|Doggett|2009|p=73}}

In March 1970, a month before [[the Beatles' break-up]], Boyd moved with Harrison to [[Friar Park]], a [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] [[neo-Gothic]] mansion in [[Henley-on-Thames]].{{sfn|Browne|2011|pp=83–84}} By this point, Harrison's devotion to Indian spirituality, particularly the [[Hare Krishna movement]], had begun to divide the couple.{{sfn|Greene|2006|p=197}}{{sfn|Doggett|2009|p=91}} They were also unsuccessful in starting a family, and Harrison would not consider [[adoption]].{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=36}}{{refn|group=nb|Harrison told friends that he was infertile, a gesture that they realised was out of consideration for Boyd, given that he was able to father a child with his second wife, [[Olivia Arias]].{{sfn|Tillery|2011|pp=91–93}}}} Boyd resumed her modelling career in May 1971, in defiance of Harrison's spiritual convictions.{{sfn|Huntley|2006|pp=87–88}}{{sfn|Greene|2006|pp=197–98}} In 1973, she had an affair with [[The Faces|Faces]] guitarist [[Ronnie Wood]].{{sfn|Huntley|2006|p=99}} Boyd said her decision to leave Harrison in 1974{{sfn|Doggett|2009|p=209}} was based largely upon his repeated infidelities, culminating in his affair with Starr's wife [[Maureen Starkey Tigrett|Maureen]], which Boyd called "the final straw".{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=179–180}}{{refn|group=nb|Boyd characterised the last year of her marriage as "fuelled by [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and [[cocaine]]", and claimed "George used coke excessively, and I think it changed him&nbsp;... it froze his emotions and hardened his heart."{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=175–76}}}}

Author Ian Inglis, discussing Harrison's 1973 song "[[So Sad]]", describes Boyd as the musician's "closest companion" and someone who shared in his "triumphs and tragedies". Among these key events, Inglis lists the international [[Beatlemania]] phenomenon, the Beatles' decision to retire from live performance, the 1967 [[Summer of Love]], Epstein's death, the creation of [[Apple Corps]], the Beatles' exploration of Indian spirituality, the band's break-up, Harrison's ascendancy as a songwriter and then as a solo artist, and his [[Concert for Bangladesh|Bangladesh aid project]].{{sfn|Inglis|2010|p=45}} The couple's divorce was finalised on 9 June 1977.{{sfn|Badman|2001|p=210}} Boyd's solicitor, Paddy Grafton-Green of the London firm [[Theodore Goddard]], later remarked on the sensitivity shown by each party towards the other, which he found particularly rare in his experience of high-stakes divorces. He said: "There was no overreacting, no greed or playing with each other's emotions – I wish all divorces were so well handled."{{sfn|Greene|2006|pp=208–09}}

===Marriage to Eric Clapton===
[[File:Clapton.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.6|Clapton on stage, 19 June 1977]]
In the late 1960s, Clapton and Harrison became close friends and began writing and recording music together. This is when Clapton fell in love with Boyd.{{sfn|Doggett|2009|p=261}} In an effort to satisfy his infatuation, Clapton briefly dated Boyd's sister Paula.{{sfn|Clayson|2003|p=241}} His 1970 album with [[Derek and the Dominos]], ''[[Layla and Other Assorted Love Songs]]'', was written to proclaim his love for Boyd, particularly the hit song "[[Layla]]".<ref name="CNN2005"/> Clapton drew inspiration from ''The Story of Layla and Majnun'' by Persian writer [[Nizami Ganjavi|Nizami]], casting himself as the poet driven to madness by his unattainable love.{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=123}} When Boyd rebuffed his advances in late 1970, Clapton descended into [[heroin addiction]] and self-imposed exile for three years.{{sfn|Tillery|2011|p=93}} Once cured of his addiction in 1974, Clapton again pursued Boyd, who now agreed to leave Harrison. She and Clapton were married in 1979.{{sfn|Doggett|2009|p=261}} They remained friendly with Harrison, who took to calling Clapton his "husband-in-law".{{sfn|Greene|2006|p=208}}

Boyd soon struggled within the marriage and took to drinking heavily, but these difficulties were masked by her public image with Clapton.{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=304–07}} He later admitted to being a "full-blown" [[Alcoholism|alcoholic]] who was often violent towards his wife.{{sfn|Harry|2003|pp=124–25}} Boyd left Clapton in April 1987 and divorced him in 1989. Her stated reasons were Clapton's years of alcoholism, as well as his numerous affairs,<ref name="Meacham/SMH" /> including one with Italian actress [[Lory Del Santo]].<ref name="Telegraph1999">{{cite web|first=Judith|last=Woods|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/1999/03/17/tlboyd17.html|title=It's amazing we're still alive|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 March 1999|accessdate=5 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508004035/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F1999%2F03%2F17%2Ftlboyd17.html|archivedate=8 May 2008|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1989, her divorce was granted on the grounds of "infidelity and unreasonable behaviour".{{sfn|Boyd|2007|p=263}} She subsequently suspected that Clapton's pursuit of her when she was married to Harrison "had more to do" with the competitive aspect of the two musicians' friendship, and that "Eric just wanted what George had."{{sfn|Reid|2006|p=ix}}

In 2007, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' referred to Boyd as a "legendary rock muse" for her role in inspiring the music of Harrison and then Clapton.<ref name="RS/SpillsBeans">{{cite magazine|author=Rolling Stone staff|url=https://www.rollingstone.com:80/music/news/former-george-harrison-and-eric-clapton-muse-pattie-boyd-spills-the-beans-20070806|title=Former George Harrison, Eric Clapton Muse Pattie Boyd Spills the Beans|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=6 August 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917202738/http://www.rollingstone.com:80/music/news/former-george-harrison-and-eric-clapton-muse-pattie-boyd-spills-the-beans-20070806 |archivedate=17 September 2017|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Roger Cormier of ''[[mental floss]]'' similarly recognises her as "one of the most important muses in rock and roll history".<ref>{{cite web|first=Roger|last=Cormier|title=Layla in Real Life: 10 Songs Written About Pattie Boyd|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/78851/layla-real-life-10-songs-written-about-pattie-boyd |publisher=[[Mental Floss|mentalfloss.com]]|date=28 April 2016|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> In addition to "Layla", she was the inspiration for Clapton's songs "[[Bell Bottom Blues (Derek and the Dominos song)|Bell Bottom Blues]]" and "[[Wonderful Tonight]]".{{sfn|Boyd|2007|pp=153, 201–02}}

===Marriage to Rod Weston===
Boyd met property developer Rod Weston in 1991.{{sfn|Harry|2003|p=40}} The couple were married on 29 April 2015 in a ceremony held at the Register Office in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea Old Town Hall]], London. Weston was quoted as saying, "It's almost our silver anniversary so we thought we had better get on with it."<ref name="Furness"/>

==Autobiography==
In August 2007, [[Headline Publishing Group|Headline Review]] published Boyd's autobiography, titled ''[[Wonderful Today]]''<ref name="RS/SpillsBeans" /> and co-written with journalist and broadcaster [[Penny Junor]].<ref name="Meacham/SMH">{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Meacham|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2007/07/03/1183351210250.html|title=Beatle's muse comes clean|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=4 July 2007|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Re-titled ''Wonderful Tonight: George Harrison, Eric Clapton, and Me'' for the US market, the book contains many of Boyd's photographs.<ref name="BoydBookAmazon">{{cite book|first=Boyd, Pattie|last=Junor, Penny|title=Wonderful Today: The Autobiography of Pattie Boyd|publisher=Headline Review|isbn=0755316428 }}</ref><ref name="Meacham/SMH" /> At the time, she was said to be looking forward to the idea of her book competing against Clapton's autobiography, which was published concurrently.<ref name="Meacham/SMH" /> Boyd carried out interviews to promote the release.<ref name="RS/SpillsBeans" />

Reviewing ''Wonderful Today'' for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', [[Lynn Barber]] described it as "absolutely gripping" and a memoir that "gives more insight into the weirdness of rock-star life than anything I have ever read".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/non_fictionreviews/3667995/Pattie-Boyds-side-of-the-story.html|first=Lynn|last=Barber|title=Pattie Boyd's side of the story|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 September 2007|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> In the United States, the book debuted at the top of the [[New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/23/books/bestseller/0923besthardnonfiction.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=New York Times Best Seller list for 9/23/07|accessdate=5 July 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

